# TypeScript Client Quality

Use this rule when editing client TypeScript or Vue components.

## Principles

- Keep changes small and local to the task.
- Prefer clear names, early returns, and simple control flow.
- Avoid `any`; use `unknown` at external boundaries and narrow it.
- Prefer `const`; use `let` only when reassignment is needed.
- Use existing composables, stores, utilities, and components before adding new abstractions.
- Add comments only for non-obvious intent or constraints.

## Vue And Events

- Prefix event handlers with `handle` when they are passed to templates or child components.
- Move complex template expressions into `computed` values or small helpers.
- Keep business workflows in stores/composables instead of large page components.
- Use conditional classes or computed class lists when it improves readability; do not over-abstract one-off classes.

## Safety

- Treat API responses, persisted store data, URL params, and browser state as untrusted until validated or narrowed.
- Never use raw `v-html`; only use sanitized HTML through existing utilities.
- Use safe URL/image helpers for dynamic navigation or media sources.

## Verification

- Prefer focused Vitest files, `npm run typecheck`, or `npm run lint` for touched client code.
- Run Playwright only when the user asks, CI is failing, or the change affects a critical browser flow.
